05639nam a22006495i 9780773596122DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735961227 a10.1515/97807735961222doi  a(DE-B1597)657529  a(OCoLC)900244350  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE78.C2bB56 2014eb 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a323.1197/07100aBlockades or Breakthroughs? :bAboriginal Peoples Confront the Canadian State /ced. by Yale D. Belanger, P. Whitney Lackenbauer. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource :bmaps, 1 table, 1 diagram  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPoint Pelee's Summer of Discontent -- tThe Nature of a Blockade: Environmental Politics and the Haida Action on Lyell Island, British Columbia -- tLubicon Lake: The Success and Failure of Radical Activism -- t“The War Will Be Won When the Last Low-Level Flying Happens Here in Our Home”: Innu Opposition to Low-Level Flying in Labrador -- tA Bridge Too Far? The Oka Crisis -- tThe Oldman River Dam and the Lonefighters' Response to Environmental Incursion -- tThe Tragedy of Ipperwash -- tThe Gustafsen Lake Standoff -- tSeeking Relief: The Dispute in Burnt Church (Esgenoôpetitj) -- tTechnological Regionalisms: The Fieldwork Residency Project -- tYour Home on Native Land? Conflict and Controversy at Caledonia and the Six Nations of the Grand River -- tContributors -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBlockades have become a common response to Canada's failure to address and resolve the legitimate claims of First Nations. Blockades or Breakthroughs? debates the importance and effectiveness of blockades and occupations as political and diplomatic tools for Aboriginal people. The adoption of direct action tactics like blockades and occupations is predicated on the idea that something drastic is needed for Aboriginal groups to break an unfavourable status quo, overcome structural barriers, and achieve their goals. But are blockades actually "breakthroughs"? What are the objectives of Aboriginal people and communities who adopt this approach? How can the success of these methods be measured? This collection offers an in-depth survey of occupations, blockades, and their legacies, from 1968 to the present. Individual case studies situate specific blockades and conflicts in historical context, examine each group’s reasons for occupation, and analyze the media labels and frames applied to both Aboriginal and state responses. Direct action tactics remain a powerful political tool for First Nations in Canada. The authors of Blockades or Breakthroughs? Argue that blockades and occupations are instrumental, symbolic, and complex events that demand equally multifaceted responses. Contributors include Yale D. Belanger, Tom Flanagan, Sarah King, P. Whitney Lackenbauer, David Rossiter, John Sandlos, Nick Shrubsole, and Timothy Winegard.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndians of North America -- Canada -- Government relations. 0aIndigenous peoples -- Legal status, laws, etc. -- Canada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aBelanger, Yale D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelanger, Yale D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFlanagan, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGulewitsch, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Sarah J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLackenbauer, P. Whitney, econt